          <mj-spacer height="30px" />
          <mj-text mj-class="purple h2">Phishing: Malware distributors are switching to less suspicious file types</mj-text>
          <mj-image src="http://images.techhive.com/images/article/2017/01/dsc02671-100706102-large.jpg"></mj-image>
          <mj-text>After aggressively using JavaScript email attachments to distribute malware for the past year, attackers are now switching to less suspicious file types to trick users. Last week, researchers from the Microsoft Malware Protection Center warned about a new wave of spam emails that carried malicious .LNK files inside ZIP archives. Those files had malicious PowerShell scripts attached to them. </mj-text>
          <mj-text>In the recent campaign seen by Microsoft, the malicious LNK files contained a PowerShell script that downloaded and installed the Kovter click fraud trojan. Another file type used to distribute malware in recent months has been SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics). While many people correctly associate .SVG files with images, it's a little-known fact that such files can actually contain JavaScript.</mj-text>
          <mj-button background-color="#992785" href="http://www.csoonline.com/article/3166152/security/malware-distributors-are-switching-to-less-suspicious-file-types.html">
            Read More
          </mj-button>
        </mj-column>
      </mj-section>


      <!-- Additional Articles -->
